'''<big>Design Goals</big>'''
* Simple * Expressive * Minimal keywords * Functional/Imperative/Object-oriented * Extensible * Simple ---- [[../PrototypesVsClasses|Next]] Previous [[../|Top]]
{{BookCat}}

'''<big>Inheritance via Concatenation</big>'''

The idea is from Antero Taivalsaari.

Concatenate the environment of the subclass and
the superclass.

Now, looking up a component of a superclass is exactly
the same process as looking up a component of the
subclass.

    class g
        {
        var x = 2;
        function me("I'm g");
        }

    class f extends g
        {
        var y = 4;
        function me("I'm f");
        }

Make some objects:

    var gobj = new g;
    var fobj = new f;

''gobj'''s environment:

{| border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" align="center"
! variable
! value
|- 
| ''x''
| 2
|-
| me
| lambda() { "I'm g"; }
|}


''fobj'''s environment:

{| border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="5" align="center"
! variable
! value
|- 
| ''y''
| 4
|-
| ''me''
| lambda() { "I'm f"; }
|-
| ''x''
| 3
|-
| ''me''
| lambda() { "I'm g"; }

|}


----

[[../SupportedModesOfInheritance|Next]]
[[../EnvironmentsAsObjects|Previous]]
[[../|Top]]

{{BookCat}}

'''<big>Inheritance Implementation Strategies</big>'''

So how to implement the big three via concatenation inheritance?

For simplicity, let's assume a sequential search of the environment
table when trying to resolve a variable.

Will use Sway syntax from here on out.

The quintessential class/constructor:

    function node(item,next)
        {
        this;
        }

Making nodes:

    var items = node(1,node(2,node(3,:null)));

Or shorthand:

    var # = node;
    var items = right(1 # 2 # 3 # :null);

Using nodes:

    while (items != :null)
        {
        inspect(items . item);
        items = items . next;
        }

The function [[../right|''right'']] can be written in Sway using reflection.

----

[[../ExtensionInheritance|Next]]
[[../SupportedModesOfInheritance|Previous]]
[[../|Top]]

{{BookCat}}

'''<big>Extension Inheritance</big>'''

Extension inheritance: whereby the subclass adds features not found 
in the superclass.

    function super(a)
        {
        var b = a + 1 * (a - 1);
        this;
        }

    function sub()
        {
        var c = 3;
        extends(super(c * c));
        }

Now we make a ''sub'' object:

    var s = sub();
    inspect(s . b);

The output is:

    s . b is 80

----

[[../ReificationInheritance|Next]]
[[../InheritanceImplementationStrategies|Previous]]
[[../|Top]]

{{BookCat}}

'''<big>Reification Inheritance</big>'''

Reification inheritance: whereby the subclass completes (or partially completes)
an incomplete superclass.

    function super()
        {
        function a(x) { b(x * x); }
        this;
        }

    function sub()
        {
        function b(y) { y + 1 * (y - 1); }
        extends(super());
        }

Now we make a ''sub'' object:

    var s = sub();
    inspect(s . a(3));

The output is:

    s . a(3) is 80

Sway allows you to look at the concatenated environment:

    ppObject(s);

yields:

    <OBJECT 5651>:
        context: <OBJECT 654>
        dynamicContext: <OBJECT 654>
        callDepth: 1
        constructor: <function sub()>
        this: <OBJECT 5651>
        b: <function b(y)>
        a: <function a(x)>

----

[[../VariationInheritance|Next]]
[[../ExtensionInheritance|Previous]]
[[../|Top]]

{{BookCat}}

'''<big>Variation Inheritance</big>'''

Variation inheritance: whereby the subclass changes a behavior of the super class.

    function super()
        {
        var greeting = "hello";
        function a() { greeting; }
        this;
        }

    function sub()
        {
        function a() { "well, " + a . prior() + " there!"; }
        extends(super());
        }

    var s = sub();

    println(s . a());

The output is:

    well, hello there!

Looking at the ''s'' object gives:

    <OBJECT 2611>:
        context: <OBJECT 654>
        dynamicContext: <OBJECT 654>
        callDepth: 1
        constructor: <function sub()>
        this: <OBJECT 2611>
        a: <function a()>
        a: <function a()>
        greeting: "hello"

----

[[../PublicAndPrivateComponents|Next]]
[[../ReificationInheritance|Previous]]
[[../|Top]]

{{BookCat}}

'''<big>Class and Object Components</big>'''

''Class component'': shared by all instances

''Object component'': unique for each instance

Could use a global variable...

    var shared_count = 0;

    function z()
        {
        var count = 0;
        shared_count += 1;
        count += 1;
        this;
        }

    function x()
        {
        extends(z());
        }

    inspect(x() . shared_count);
    inspect(x() . count);
    inspect(x() . shared_count);

Results are as expected:

    x() . shared_count is 1
    x() . count is 1
    x() . shared_count is 3

Not very [[../ClassAndObjectComponents2|satisfying]]...

----

[[../Examples|Next]]
[[../PublicAndPrivateComponents|Previous]]
[[../|Top]]

{{BookCat}}

'''<big>Examples</big>'''

How about ''with''?

    function with(obj,$actions)
        {
        $actions . context = obj;
        force($actions);
        }

Let's create an object:

    function f(x) { var y = x + 1; this;}

    var o = f(3);

Now let's modify its slots:

    with (o)
        {
        x = 10;
        y = 13;
        }

Did it work?

    inspect(o . x);
    inspect(o . y);

Output:

    o . x is 10
    o . y is 13


----

[[../Examples2|Next]]
[[../ClassAndObjectComponents|Previous]]
[[../|Top]]

{{BookCat}}

'''<big>Class and Object Components, continued</big>'''

Here's an attempt...

    var z =
    {
    var z_shared = { var count = 0; this; };

    function z()
        {
        var shared = z_shared;
        var count = 0;
        shared . count += 1;
        count += 1;
        this;
        }
    };

    function x()
        {
        extends(z());
        }

Testing...

    inspect(x() . shared . count);
    inspect(x() . count);
    inspect(x() . shared . count);

Output is as desired:

    x() . shared . count is 1
    x() . count is 1
    x() . shared . count is 3

The beauty of [[../ClassAndObjectComponents3|concatenation]]...

{{BookCat}}

'''<big>Class and Object Components, continued</big>'''

What about overriding simple variables?

    function z()
        {
        var value = 3;
        function getvalue() { value; }
        this;
        }

    function x()
        {
        var value = 4;
        extends(z());
        }

    var obj = x();

What should <tt>obj . getValue()</tt> produce?

----
[[../PublicAndPrivateComponents|Previous]]
[[../Examples|Next]]
[[../|Top]]

{{BookCat}}

'''<big>Public and Private Components</big>'''

We overload assignment so that only variables can appear
on the left hand side of the assignment operator.

    function =($a,b)
        {
        var assign = shadowed(:=);

        if (type($a . code) != :VARIABLE)
           {
           throw(:restrictedAssignment,
               "you are only allowed to assign to simple variables");
           }

        $a assign b;
        }

So, anything like:

    x . a = 3;

throws an exception.

Since ''setters'' can access the variables directly,
they are not affected by this change.

----

